   <mods:abstract>Regrets the afflictions mentioned in Jay's last letter and gives an
            account of illnesses in his own family. Discusses the properties and use of plaster and
            other fertilizers. John Jay is right in his estimate of the probable lack of success
            Peters will have in trying to bring into fashion a spirit of agricultural enquiry and
            improvement. The spirit of the times is to aim at immediate advantages, and it is in the
            nature of man to enjoy present benefits. Agrees with John Jay's view of the state of
            Europe, and that nothing like an "overturn" will happen during present times in America.
            "The little Tornado here, has really effected much good;" the minority profits from the
            division of the majority.</mods:abstract>
